<br>
All missions canm be broken down into basic components:<br>
HLLV- Heavy lift launch vehicle<br>
TMI-Trans-Mars injection stage<br>
Transfer Habitat<br>
MDV-Mars decent vehicle (lander)<br>
Surface Hab<br>
Cargo Lander<br>
MAV-Mars Accent Vehicle<br>
TEI-Trans Earth Injection<br>
<br>
Many missions combine these to save mass, as will ours. As I currently see it the breakdown is thus:<br>
<br>
HLLV: I chose an option designed but rejected by NASA in their DRM 1.0. It is option #2, designed as a shuttle derived HLLV with three Rs-68's in the first stage, one in the second, and seven strap on boosters each with a RD-170 engine. This uses a mininum of new technology and can lift 209mT to a 220n.mi. circular orbit.<br>
<br>
TMI/TEI: This consists of a undetermined nuclear propulsion system. A seperate TMI satge allows for faster transist then a direct throw to Mars. An SCNTR or VASMIR would probibly require refueling in Mars orbit to return, to keep down on mass. Non-human payloads could be thrown directly to Mars to save on cost.<br>
<br>
HABs: Having a reusible TMI stage requires a transfer habitat. This provides living space and solar shelter for the crew. It is also the crews home if they must abort to orbit. Having two surface habitats provides an extra level of safety should one fail. It also provides more labratory space. Inflatible habs could be placed on one of the cargo landers. NASA predicted that an inflatible surface habitat took up as much space and mass as a presurized rover. Each Hab would land a 100kWe reactor.<br>
<br>
MA/DV: I plan to use a NTR accent/deccent vehicle, or a Nuclear rocket using Indigonous Martian Fuel (NIMF). A NIMF provides many advanteges. It requires no fuel from Earth to produce its return fuel, just compress Martian atmosphere. With a 25kWe bimodal power system it could fuel itself in 30 days. They could be used a emergency backup power sources. The NIMF solves one of the bigest worries about an orbital rondevous, what if you miss? The NIMF would just reenter, reland and give you a second shot. Each would carry a space parachute, giving the crew three shots at connecting to the return ship. If used as a global hopper, the chute could be released in an emergancy if the engine goes SCRAM, saving the crew. And by returning it to Earth it could be reused.<br>
<br>
Cargo Lander: These would carry the rovers, tools, spares, ie stuff. One could include a machine shop to make replacement parts or repair instruments if neccicary. I like NASA's three rovers, two unpressurized, one pressurized. These landers can be based on the Habs to cut down on costs.<br>
<br>
Satellites: I was trying to find out the mass of a comsat(i failed), great minds think alike, one which would supply a seperate radio signal to the surface, nothing fancy there is no worry of jamming. A group of 12-16 should provide communication over the entire planet, and by broadcasting signals, could be used to create a Martian GPS network, easing exploration and landing of components. If each is a tonne(This may be over, or under), 12-16 tonnes is an acceptible cargo mass. It is included below.<br>
<br>
I worked out roughly that with eight launches of a HLLV, in this case using a EPPP drive, A ship could be put together in orbit carrying 230 tons of destination payload, combined with three precursor direct to Mars throws, landing two 60mT habs, two 50mT landers, and three 60mT Cargo landers. 400mT on Mars. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ihrenes>Ihrenes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/18/02 6:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear Mars Mission</span><hr size=1> Hi, <br>
