<br>
Of course we want to keep the crew safe, that's why we are using nuclear. Mars is well suited for nuclear power on the surface. Using internal combustion generators for regular power production requires a prodigous amount of fuel be flown to and stored on Mars on top of the mass of the generator. Solar pannels are vulnerible to intense Martian duststorms, which can both damage the surface, or block out the sun for days or weeks. Solar actually is a lot heavier then nuclear reactors, a 120kWe solar system would weigh 33.4 tonnes, more then twice a SP-100 for less output. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 438<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/19/02 12:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear Mars Mission</span><hr size=1> Look at the number of nuclear powered ships that are safely operated in the Navy.  Their crews don't tend to fall dead or accumulate huge doses of radiation.  With proper shielding a nuclear reactor wouldn't be as big as a health threat as a lot of people make it out to be.  And once the astronauts have landed, they can always protect themselves from radiation even further by keeping the reactor a long distance from the hab and perhaps put it in a crater or use some other geologic feature to block radiation that much more.  Nuclear energy is just way more efficient th