I finally found the article on those fission batteries I was talking about.  The caption in the graphic gives a brief overview of the battery.  The battery would generate electric current directly from fission without needing to generate steam or utilizing the heat.  According to the article a baseball sized battery would generate about 4 million volts and would be particularly useful for powering small probes. Hmm, might prove handy for jumpstarting the rover when someone forgets to turn off the headlights.   Here's a quote:<br>
<br>
&quot;As part of a NERI-funded project, a Sandia-led<br>
team has developed three concepts for direct<br>
energy conversion “fission batteries” that produce<br>
electrical current directly from fission. Essentially,<br>
positively charged heavy atoms and electrons<br>
released during fission reactions in the fuel are<br>
separated and collected by electrodes, creating a<br>
usable voltage.&quot;  <br>
<br>
The Sandia Technology Quarterly, Spring 2002 is the source. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 11/23/02 3:50:42 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ihrenes>Ihrenes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/23/02 6:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  ADS Rule !</span><hr size=1> Mauk2, <br>
