Also, this idea is not new: I found out that it was already extenssively researched at JPL in 1963...see &quot;Fission-Fragment Conversion Reactors for Space&quot;, Nucleonics, Vol. 1, N0.4, April 1963. Authors: C.J.Heindl, W.F.Krieve, and R. V. Meghreblian.<br>
The idea is the same one, and in fact, there are many other old ideas for direct power conversion, such as: Thermionic Conversion, Thermoelectric, Fission-fragment conversion (the one now at Sandia labs.), Magneto-hydrodynamic conversion... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 132<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/29/02 12:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Direct Conversion...</span><hr size=1> Ihrenes: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Mauk2, u really like ADS?, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Yes, yes I do.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I especially like the Energy Amplifier envisioned by Carlos Rubbia of CERN.  That thing is SAFE, with multiple passive scram and cooling elements.  Plus, the lead/bismuth cooling has been extensively proofed by our new friends, the Russians.  Add in the facts that the core is sub-critical, even during decay heat management, it HAS to have the proton beam working to generate power, and if it overheats, the natural expansion of the lead/bismuth coolant floods the proton beam channel and kills the core, and you have a recipe for greatness.<br>
<br>
Granted, it does have some technical challenges, especially in the design details of the spallation target, but all in all, it seems VERY doable, and very safe, and can generate GOBS of power due to the use of thorium as fuel, and do it more cleanly than a conventional PWR.  <br>
<br>
In addition, an EA is easily run at high temperatures due to the metal coolant, which means it is readily adaptable to hydrogen generation using the iodine/sulfur catalyzed cycle.  <br>
<br>
It's just a WONDERFUL toy.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> well I am not so sure a supercritical design would weight less...why?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, an AD design is deliberately adding an extra system to the powerplant.  IE, the particle accelerator is a pure add-on, not needed for making power(if you use the right fuel).  It adds tremendous value in terrestrial applications by making the powerplant directly throttleable, but at the expense of some complexity and mass.  In a super-lightweight design, where mass is a critical piece of the puzzle, leaving off that extra system and relying on traditional controls would result in a lighter plant.<br>
<br>
Atomicrod, of Adams Atomic Engines, argues eloquently for pebble-based &quot;micro-fission&quot; plants.  For very small power installations, and assuming you could show sufficient durability of the fuel pebbles in that usage, then that sort of a super-critical but density controlled reactor could probably be made much lighter than a similar AD system.<br>
